{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Scrollspy · Stisla v3{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Scrollspy</h1>
    <p class="lead">A behavior that highlights nav links as their sections scroll into view.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Basic</h2>
    <p>Put <code>data-bs-spy="scroll"</code> on the scrollable container and point <code>data-bs-target</code> at the nav. Wrap each section in a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> whose <code>id</code> matches a nav link's <code>href</code>. The wrapper is the observed element, so Bootstrap can track which section is in view across the full content block, not just the heading line.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div>
      <nav id="ss-basic-nav" class="nav nav-pills mb-2">
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-basic-1">Overview</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-basic-2">Setup</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-basic-3">Usage</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-basic-4">Reference</a>
      </nav>
      <div data-bs-spy="scroll" data-bs-target="#ss-basic-nav" data-bs-root-margin="0px 0px -40%" data-bs-smooth-scroll="true" tabindex="0" class="border rounded p-3 overflow-auto" style="height: 220px;">
        <div id="ss-basic-1">
          <h4>Overview</h4>
          <p>Scrollspy reports which section is in view by toggling <code>.active</code> on the matching link. It doesn't draw anything itself.</p>
          <p>Under the hood it runs an IntersectionObserver against the elements your nav points at. The links can live anywhere on the page; only their <code>href</code> needs to match.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="ss-basic-2">
          <h4>Setup</h4>
          <p>Give the scroll container <code>data-bs-spy="scroll"</code> and point <code>data-bs-target</code> at the nav whose links should flip.</p>
          <p>Each link's <code>href</code> must reference an <code>id</code> that lives inside the scroll container. Bootstrap reads the hash, not the link text.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="ss-basic-3">
          <h4>Usage</h4>
          <p>Add sections, give them ids, and add nav links to match. Adding or removing sections at runtime requires calling <code>refresh()</code> on the instance after the DOM changes.</p>
          <p>The container needs a height and <code>overflow-auto</code> so it actually scrolls. Without those, every section is in view at once and the behavior is a no-op.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="ss-basic-4">
          <h4>Reference</h4>
          <p>Tunable options are <code>data-bs-root-margin</code>, <code>data-bs-threshold</code>, and <code>data-bs-smooth-scroll</code>. The first two map directly to IntersectionObserver.</p>
          <p>The legacy <code>data-bs-offset</code> attribute still works but is deprecated. Prefer <code>data-bs-root-margin</code> for new code.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>List group target</h2>
    <p>The nav doesn't have to be a <code>.nav</code>. Any container whose direct <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> children carry hash hrefs works, including <code>.list-group</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row g-3">
      <div class="col-md-4">
        <div id="ss-list-nav" class="list-group">
          <a class="list-group-item list-group-item-action" href="#ss-list-1">Identity</a>
          <a class="list-group-item list-group-item-action" href="#ss-list-2">Billing</a>
          <a class="list-group-item list-group-item-action" href="#ss-list-3">Members</a>
          <a class="list-group-item list-group-item-action" href="#ss-list-4">Audit log</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-md-8">
        <div data-bs-spy="scroll" data-bs-target="#ss-list-nav" data-bs-root-margin="0px 0px -40%" data-bs-smooth-scroll="true" tabindex="0" class="border rounded p-3 overflow-auto" style="height: 260px;">
          <div id="ss-list-1">
            <h4>Identity</h4>
            <p>Set the workspace name, slug, and primary owner. The slug becomes part of every shareable URL the team hands out.</p>
            <p>Renaming the workspace updates the display name everywhere but keeps the slug stable, so existing links keep working.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-list-2">
            <h4>Billing</h4>
            <p>Manage the plan, payment method, and invoice history. Plan changes take effect at the next billing cycle.</p>
            <p>Annual plans get a discount that applies on renewal, not retroactively to the active period.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-list-3">
            <h4>Members</h4>
            <p>Invite teammates by email and assign roles. Owners can promote and demote; admins can invite but not delete the workspace.</p>
            <p>Pending invitations expire after seven days. Resending refreshes the link without losing the original role assignment.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-list-4">
            <h4>Audit log</h4>
            <p>A rolling 90 days of permission changes, exports, and destructive actions. Older entries can be downloaded as CSV.</p>
            <p>Each entry records the actor, the target, the action, and the source IP. The log is read-only even to owners.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Smooth scroll</h2>
    <p>Add <code>data-bs-smooth-scroll="true"</code> and clicking a nav link scrolls to the matching section instead of jumping. The active state still updates from the scroll position, so smooth scroll plays well with manual scrolling.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div>
      <nav id="ss-smooth-nav" class="nav nav-pills mb-2">
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-smooth-1">Step 1</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-smooth-2">Step 2</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-smooth-3">Step 3</a>
      </nav>
      <div data-bs-spy="scroll" data-bs-target="#ss-smooth-nav" data-bs-root-margin="0px 0px -40%" data-bs-smooth-scroll="true" tabindex="0" class="border rounded p-3 overflow-auto" style="height: 200px;">
        <div id="ss-smooth-1">
          <h4>Step 1</h4>
          <p>Connect a source. Stisla supports any plain HTTPS endpoint that returns JSON.</p>
          <p>The connection is validated on save, so a bad URL fails fast instead of breaking the next sync.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="ss-smooth-2">
          <h4>Step 2</h4>
          <p>Map fields. Each source field can route to one destination column, with an optional transform applied in transit.</p>
          <p>Transforms run on the worker, so they don't slow down the sync write. The library covers casts, regex extracts, and date reformatting.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="ss-smooth-3">
          <h4>Step 3</h4>
          <p>Schedule the sync. Cron syntax and the human shorthand both work. Test runs don't count against the quota.</p>
          <p>A failing run pauses the schedule and pings the workspace owner. Resuming requires a manual unblock so a broken integration can't drain the budget.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Nested nav</h2>
    <p>Nested links get nested active states. Use a <code>.nav</code> with sub-<code>.nav</code> children, and Bootstrap marks the parent active when any child is.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row g-3">
      <div class="col-md-4">
        <nav id="ss-nested-nav" class="nav nav-pills flex-column">
          <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-nested-1">Getting started</a>
          <nav class="nav nav-pills flex-column">
            <a class="nav-link ms-3 my-1" href="#ss-nested-1-1">Install</a>
            <a class="nav-link ms-3 my-1" href="#ss-nested-1-2">First run</a>
          </nav>
          <a class="nav-link" href="#ss-nested-2">Configuration</a>
          <nav class="nav nav-pills flex-column">
            <a class="nav-link ms-3 my-1" href="#ss-nested-2-1">Tokens</a>
            <a class="nav-link ms-3 my-1" href="#ss-nested-2-2">Themes</a>
          </nav>
        </nav>
      </div>
      <div class="col-md-8">
        <div data-bs-spy="scroll" data-bs-target="#ss-nested-nav" data-bs-root-margin="0px 0px -40%" data-bs-smooth-scroll="true" tabindex="0" class="border rounded p-3 overflow-auto" style="height: 280px;">
          <div id="ss-nested-1">
            <h4>Getting started</h4>
            <p>This guide walks through the install and the first successful run. Skip ahead if you've shipped a Stisla project before.</p>
            <p>The setup assumes a recent Node version and a bundler that can resolve ESM. Vite, Webpack 5, and Rollup all work out of the box.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-nested-1-1">
            <h5>Install</h5>
            <p>Pull the package from npm. Stisla ships an ESM build and a UMD build, so any bundler picks the right one automatically.</p>
            <p>Peer dependencies are listed in the package manifest. The framework expects Bootstrap 5.3 as a peer; pin the version explicitly in production.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-nested-1-2">
            <h5>First run</h5>
            <p>Import the stylesheet and the JS entry. The framework auto-initializes declarative behaviors on load.</p>
            <p>Open any page and inspect the body for the <code>stisla-ready</code> class. If it's missing, the bundle didn't execute and the data-API behaviors will stay dormant.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-nested-2">
            <h4>Configuration</h4>
            <p>Most projects ship without editing a single SCSS file. When you do need to tweak, override tokens before importing the stylesheet.</p>
            <p>The token surface is intentionally narrow. Anything outside the documented variables is implementation detail and may change between minor versions.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-nested-2-1">
            <h5>Tokens</h5>
            <p>Color, spacing, radius, and shadow tokens live in a single map. Override the keys you need; the rest cascade from the defaults.</p>
            <p>Token overrides resolve at build time. Runtime theming should go through the CSS variables that the tokens generate.</p>
          </div>
          <div id="ss-nested-2-2">
            <h5>Themes</h5>
            <p>Light and dark themes are driven by <code>data-theme</code> on <code>&lt;html&gt;</code>, or the <code>.dark</code> class for class-based switchers. Custom themes follow the same selector pattern.</p>
            <p>A theme is just a scoped block of CSS variables. Defining one is a matter of authoring the overrides and naming the attribute value.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Tuning activation</h2>
    <p>Under the hood the behavior runs on IntersectionObserver. Two attributes shape when a section counts as "in view".</p>
    <p><code>data-bs-root-margin</code> takes the same string as the IntersectionObserver option. A negative bottom margin like <code>0px 0px -40%</code> delays activation until the section is well into the visible area, which feels more accurate when sections are short.</p>
    <p><code>data-bs-threshold</code> sets how much of a section must intersect before it activates. Pass a comma-separated list to fire at multiple steps, e.g. <code>"0.1,0.5,1"</code>.</p>
    <p>If the page changes after load (sections appended, links rewritten), grab the instance and call <code>refresh()</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='js') %}
    const el = document.querySelector('[data-bs-spy="scroll"]');
    const spy = Stisla.bs.ScrollSpy.getInstance(el);
    spy.refresh();
    {% endcall %}
  </section>
{% endblock %}
